## Quiz

?? Why does BFS guarantee shortest-path (in edges) from the source to any reachable node in an unweighted graph?
>> Because BFS explores nodes in order of increasing distance from the source: all nodes at distance $k$ are visited before any node at distance $k+1$. When a node is first reached, it must be via a shortest path.

?? What changes if we use a LIFO stack instead of a FIFO queue?
>> You get depth-first search (DFS). It dives down one branch to the bottom before backtracking, rather than exploring level by level. DFS uses less memory on wide graphs but no longer finds shortest paths.
